the water main broke;
felt like an earthquake.

00:11.800 --> 00:14.800
Coffins were bursting
out of the ground.

00:16.500 --> 00:17.900
Are you all right?

00:18.600 --> 00:21.100
I've had some stomach
problems lately.

00:21.200 --> 00:23.600
This isn't helping.

00:23.600 --> 00:25.000
Last person was buried
here over 50 years ago.

00:25.000 --> 00:26.700
I don't know how you're gonna
figure out who's who.

00:26.800 --> 00:28.000
With burial records,

00:28.100 --> 00:30.800
identification should be
pretty straightforward.

00:30.800 --> 00:32.500
All right, let's see.

00:32.600 --> 00:33.800
Female...

00:33.900 --> 00:35.600
40 to 50 years old,

00:35.800 --> 00:37.700
severe osteoporosis,

00:37.800 --> 00:41.700
dress and jewelry place burial
around the late 19th century.

00:43.200 --> 00:44.500
This one's in pieces.

00:46.000 --> 00:47.000
What's going on here?

00:47.400 --> 00:49.000
Lorraine said you're
giving them church records.

00:49.100 --> 00:51.400
The burial records, Father,
so they can identify

00:51.500 --> 00:53.000
and reinter the remains.

00:53.100 --> 00:56.000
Those records are
my responsibility,
Father Sands.

00:56.100 --> 00:58.200
You're to go through me before
allowing their release.

00:58.300 --> 01:00.200
I'm sorry, Father.
I saw no harm in it.

01:00.300 --> 01:01.800
I still run this parish.

01:01.900 --> 01:02.900
I understand.

01:03.300 --> 01:04.599
I'm Father William Donlan.

01:04.700 --> 01:06.700
This is Dr. Brennan
from the Jeffersonian and...

01:06.800 --> 01:08.300
They can't speak
for themselves?

01:08.900 --> 01:10.100
I'm Dr. Addy.

01:10.400 --> 01:11.400
Are you one
of those priests

01:11.500 --> 01:13.300
